    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="766"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d766">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">574.D7/1613: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HC4" type="from">Hsieh
                            Chieh-shih</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Changchun</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-23">April 23,
                            1932</date>.<lb/>[Received 5:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Minister of Foreign Affairs at Changchun has the honor to inform that government
                    of state of Manchuria desires to adhere [to] International Radiotelegraph
                    Convention of Washington<note n="87" xml:id="d766fn87">Signed November 25, 1927,
                            <ref target="frus1927v01#pg_288">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1927, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 288</ref>.</note> and general and
                    additional regulations annexed thereto. For participation in the expenses
                    International Bureau Manchuria requests assignment in 6th class. Please
                    telegraph date of notification of this adhesion to the contracting states
                    according to article 9 of this convention. Minister Foreign Affairs
                        Changchun.<note n="88" xml:id="d766fn88">In repeating this telegram to the
                        Secretary of State at Geneva, the Department’s telegram No. 58, April 25, 7
                        p.m., stated that “The Manchurian regime has not been recognized by any
                        party to the convention” and that the telegram from Changchun was being
                        filed without reply.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
